          "body": "The chapter's interpretive key is 16:20-22. The disciples' grief is real and Jesus does not minimize it — *you will weep and lament*. But grief is reframed: it is labor pain, not death-throes. A woman in labor has anguish *because her hour has come*; the same hour brings the child. The pain is not punishment or accident or absence-of-meaning — it is the very form joy takes as it is born into the world. Jesus is not promising the disciples that they will avoid sorrow; He is promising that their sorrow will *turn into* joy (*genesetai eis charan*) — the same sorrow, transmuted by resurrection. And the joy on the far side will be unremovable (*ouk airei aph' humon*, 16:22). This is the Christian theology of suffering in seed-form."
